      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Vendor Paid Advertising in Queensland Real Estate: What Sellers Pay For and Why
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Most sellers know they will have to pay for marketing but are not sure what is actually included, whether the amount is reasonable, or what questions to ask. Here is a clear account of how VPA works in Brisbane's inner east in 2027.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you engage a real estate agent to sell your property in Queensland, the agent's commission covers the agent's time, expertise, and the agency's operational costs. It does not cover the cost of marketing your property. That cost sits with you as the vendor, and it is referred to as vendor paid advertising, or VPA. Understanding exactly what VPA covers, what is and is not included in a typical budget, and how to tell whether the proposal you have been given is reasonable will help you make an informed decision before signing anything.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What vendor paid advertising is and what it is not</h2>
      <p>VPA is the marketing budget for your campaign. It covers the out-of-pocket costs of putting your property in front of buyers: listing it on the major property portals, getting professional photography taken, producing a floor plan, printing a signboard, and running any digital or social media advertising. These are direct costs that would be incurred regardless of which agent you choose, because they are primarily payments to third-party suppliers like realestate.com.au, the photography studio, and the printing company.</p>

      <p>VPA is separate from the agent's commission. Commission is paid by the seller at settlement as a percentage of the sale price (or sometimes a fixed fee), and it is only paid if the property sells. VPA is paid upfront or shortly after the campaign begins, and it is not refundable if the property does not sell. These are two distinct costs and vendors should budget for both independently rather than trying to compare proposals that bundle them together.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a typical VPA budget covers in Brisbane's inner east in 2027</h2>
      <p>Marketing costs in Brisbane's inner east have increased over the past several years as portal advertising has shifted toward premium placement models. Here is what a realistic budget covers at different spend levels:</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Entry-level ($2,000 to $3,500):</strong> A standard portal listing on realestate.com.au (not premium placement), listing on domain.com.au, professional photography, a floor plan, and a standard signboard. At this budget you are competing for attention against higher-placed listings in search results. This level may be appropriate for lower-priced properties in suburbs where buyer enquiry is strong regardless of portal position, but for most inner-east properties above $900,000, it is undershooting the market.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mid-range ($3,500 to $6,000):</strong> A Highlight or Premiere placement on realestate.com.au, listing on domain.com.au, professional photography (including aerial shots where the land is a selling feature), floor plan, signboard, and social media boosting on Facebook and Instagram. This is the level most inner-east properties at $900,000 to $1.5 million should be at if the agent is genuinely trying to maximise the buyer pool.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Premium ($6,000 and above):</strong> Top-of-search placement on realestate.com.au for an extended period, Premiere on domain.com.au, professional photography, a property video or virtual tour, aerial photography, a premium signboard, copywriting, social media advertising with a dedicated property landing page, and sometimes inclusion in the agency's own email database. Properties above $1.5 million in competitive suburbs where the buyer pool includes relocating interstate buyers will typically benefit from this level of investment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why portal placement matters and what the difference actually is</h2>
      <p>Realestate.com.au's listing tiers determine where your property appears in search results relative to others in the same suburb and price range. A standard listing appears below all Premiere and Highlight listings in search results, which means that in a suburb with active listings, a standard listing can appear on the second or third page of results before a buyer reaches it. In a market where most buyers spend no more than a few seconds deciding whether to click on a listing, page position has a direct effect on enquiry volume.</p>

      <p>Premiere placement pins your listing to the top of search results for the suburbs you are targeting for a defined period. The difference in click-through rates between Premiere and standard listings is material and documented by realestate.com.au's own data. For properties in the $900,000 to $2 million range in Brisbane's inner east, where the cost of Premiere placement is small relative to the potential price difference between attracting three competing buyers versus two, the return on the additional spend is almost always positive.</p>

      <p>Domain.com.au generates less traffic than realestate.com.au in Brisbane but is worth including in most campaigns because it reaches a different subset of buyers, particularly those who have relocated from Sydney and Melbourne where domain.com.au has a stronger market share. Listing on one portal only in 2027 limits your exposure unnecessarily.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agency rebate issue: what you are entitled to know</h2>
      <p>Some real estate agencies receive volume-based rebates from realestate.com.au, domain.com.au, and other marketing suppliers. These arrangements are commercial contracts between the agency and the supplier and are not inherently improper. What matters is disclosure. Under the Property Occupations Act 2014 (Qld), agents are required to disclose any rebates, discounts, or other benefits they receive from third parties in connection with money spent on your behalf.</p>

      <p>In practice, the rebate issue arises when an agent charges a vendor a retail price for a portal listing, receives a significant volume rebate from the portal, and retains the difference without disclosing it. The vendor believes they are paying the cost of the service, but the effective cost to the agent is lower. This is not universal and many agencies are transparent, but it is worth asking the question directly: does the agency receive any rebates from the marketing suppliers included in this proposal, and if so, are those reflected in the price being charged to me?</p>

      <p>An agent who answers this question clearly and shows you a transparent breakdown of what they pay for services versus what they are charging you is giving you a basis for comparison. An agent who is evasive or who cannot explain the pricing in detail is less transparent than you should expect when committing several thousand dollars to a marketing campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Whether VPA is the right investment: the return logic</h2>
      <p>The argument against investing in a higher marketing budget usually comes down to cost: why spend $6,000 on marketing when a basic $3,000 campaign might do the job? The answer lies in how property prices are actually set at sale. In a competitive auction or multi-offer situation, the difference between having two motivated bidders and three motivated bidders can be $30,000 to $80,000 on a well-located inner-east property. That additional buyer does not appear from nowhere: they come from seeing the listing at the right time, in a prominent position, with photography that makes the property compelling.</p>

      <p>A marketing budget is not overhead. It is an investment in the size and quality of the buyer pool that ultimately determines the sale price. The cost of underinvesting in marketing is invisible: you will not know you left $40,000 on the table because the auction ended at two bidders when it could have had three. You will simply take what you got and assume it was the market rate. In most cases, a well-deployed marketing budget in the mid-to-premium range will generate returns that are a multiple of the additional spend compared to a cut-rate campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions to ask before signing a VPA proposal</h2>
      <p>Before you commit to a marketing budget, ask your agent for a written breakdown showing each component, its cost, and what it includes. The specific questions worth asking are: what portal tier is included and for how many weeks; does the agency receive any rebates from these suppliers; is photography included, and what does it cover (external only, or internal and aerial); when are marketing costs incurred (some may be spent in the first week, others later in the campaign); and what happens to uncommitted marketing spend if the property sells in the first week.</p>

      <p>The answers will tell you whether the proposal represents genuine value or whether you are being sold a package without clarity on what you are actually getting. A good marketing proposal is transparent, itemised, and directly tied to the strategy for your specific property. A vague proposal that quotes a round number with minimal detail is worth pressing for more information before you sign.</p>

